Weekly Petroleum Status Report

Brad Horn

27-Feb-2019 Week 8

Summary

Crude Oil

U.S. crude oil production averaged 12.1 million barrels per day.

Total commercial petroleum inventories decreased last week by 17.9 million barrels last week. Since 1990, only 4 weeks have exceeded this drawdown. U.S. commercial crude oil inventories (excluding those in the Strategic Petroleum Reserve) decreased by 8.6 million barrels from the previous week. Again, this is another historic drawdown. At 445.9 million barrels, U.S. crude oil inventories are about 3% above the five year average for this time of year.

The large drawdowns are dominated by PADD3 where stocks dropped 6.7 million barrels. This can be explaine din part by an import drop of 1.6 million barrles, strong exports of 3.4 million barrels. The last two week export numbers have exceeded anythng observed over the past five years. It would be nice to see data showing where those cargoes are going..?

Gasoline

Total motor gasoline inventories decreased by 1.9 million barrels last week and are about 3% above the five year average for this time of year. Finished gasoline and blending components inventories both decreased last week. Total motor gasoline imports (including both finished gasoline and gasoline blending components) last week averaged 473,000 barrels per day

Distallates

Distillate fuel inventories decreased by 0.3 million barrels last week and are about 2% below the five year average for this time of year. Distillate fuel imports averaged 331,000 barrels per day.
